c4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/900/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/1200/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg 1200w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/1600/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg 1600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/1800/quality/85/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg 1800w" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/1100/quality/50/format/jpeg/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg" data-template="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/6000x3375+0+10/resize/{width}/quality/{quality}/format/{format}/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fc4%2F83%2F1057e47a47108f350046c68e5f69%2Fap25178748967643.jpg" class="img" alt="A family shops in a toy store in Princeton, N.J." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A family shops in a toy store in Princeton, N.J.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Matt Slocum/AP                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;When will tariffs start affecting American consumers? Shoppers have been informed by manufacturers and retailers that Trump's new tariffs on nearly all imports would significantly impact their wallets. But that impact has not materialized yet, and the full blow has yet to land. Here's &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/29/nx-s1-5477470/prices-trump-tariffs" target="_blank"&gt;what we know about why that is&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;   &lt;ul class="edTag"&gt;&lt;li&gt;💵 Some companies began stockpiling goods as early as last winter in hopes of avoiding new import taxes for an extended period.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;💵 Many importers have responded to the president's tariff announcements by canceling shipments or holding them abroad until the plan becomes clearer.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;💵 Some suppliers and retailers who are facing higher tariffs are absorbing the new tariffs as a hit to their profits because they don't want to pass the full cost on to shoppers.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;💵 Trump's 90-day summer pause has provided importers a new window to stockpile. Some stores are using this period to load up on goods for the holiday season to avoid painful price hikes.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;   &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;Today's listen&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="res1269704438" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 4026;         --source-height: 2264;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=webp 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/webp" /&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=400&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 400w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 800w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=900&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 900w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1200&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1200w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1600&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1600w, https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1800&amp;c=85&amp;f=jpeg 1800w" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" sizes="(min-width: 1025px) 650px, calc(100vw - 30px)" class="img" type="image/jpeg" /&gt;             &lt;img src="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s=1100&amp;c=50&amp;f=jpeg" data-template="https://media.npr.org/assets/img/2025/07/28/img_7136_wide-f2ec3b6cee50d934a518eab14e107c9fcdd5fddd.jpg?s={width}&amp;c={quality}&amp;f={format}" class="img" alt="A sparkly sweet treat for a sparkly sweet mix." loading="lazy" /&gt;         &lt;/picture&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="credit-caption"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-wrap"&gt;         &lt;div class="caption" aria-label="Image caption"&gt;             &lt;p&gt;                 A sparkly sweet treat for a sparkly sweet mix.                 &lt;b class="credit" aria-label="Image credit"&gt;                                          Lars Gotrich/NPR                                      &lt;/b&gt;                 &lt;b class="hide-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;             &lt;/p&gt;         &lt;/div&gt;               &lt;b class="toggle-caption"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;     &lt;/div&gt;       &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;/div&gt;    &lt;p&gt;After a hiatus, Roséwave is back by popular demand. That's no joke. Many diehard fans of the series sent messages to &lt;em&gt;All Songs Considered &lt;/em&gt;asking for its return. For those fans, congrats; your hard work has paid off. For those who aren't quite as familiar, this summer playlist series has sweet songs that provide a summer-y feel and chill vibe as you escape into the tunes. The hosts go through songs of different genres and styles to provide the perfect simple pleasures playlist. In this episode, they take the series name seriously as they crack open a bottle of rosé to discuss the music. &lt;a href="https://one.npr.org/?sharedMediaId=1256371472:1269704039" target="_blank"&gt;Listen to their selections&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2025/07/29/1256371472/rosewave-simple-pleasures" target="_blank"&gt;check out a six-hour playlist&lt;/a&gt; of additional on-theme jams.&lt;/p&gt;       &lt;h3 class="edTag"&gt;3 things to know before you&lt;/h3&gt;   &lt;div id="resg-s1-79899" class="bucketwrap image large"&gt;             &lt;div     class="imagewrap has-source-dimensions"     data-crop-type=""     style="         --source-width: 2000;         --source-height: 1125;     " &gt;         &lt;picture&gt;             &lt;source srcset="https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+0/resize/400/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F00%2Ff9%2F59b18e2c4195bdea85b5de9cde2d%2Fcopy-of-6-book-covers-2.jpg 400w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+0/resize/600/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F00%2Ff9%2F59b18e2c4195bdea85b5de9cde2d%2Fcopy-of-6-book-covers-2.jpg 600w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+0/resize/800/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F00%2Ff9%2F59b18e2c4195bdea85b5de9cde2d%2Fcopy-of-6-book-covers-2.jpg 800w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+0/resize/900/quality/85/format/webp/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fnpr-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F00%2Ff9%2F59b18e2c4195bdea85b5de9cde2d%2Fcopy-of-6-book-covers-2.jpg 900w, https://npr.brightspotcdn.com/dims3/default/strip/false/crop/2000x1125+0+0/re